Let $x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n$ be such numbers. By AM-GM, we have 
\begin{align*}
\frac{x_1 + x_2 + \dots + x_n}{n} \ge (x_1x_2\cdots x_n)^{\frac 1n},
\end{align*}
or
\begin{align*}
\frac{1000}{n} \ge (x_1x_2\cdots x_n)^{\frac 1n}.
\end{align*}
Raising both sides to the fourth power, we get 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1000^4}{n^4} \ge (x_1x_2\cdots x_n)^{\frac 4n}.
\end{align*}

On the other hand, by AM-GM, we have 
\begin{align*}
\frac{x_1^4 + x_2^4 + \dots + x_n^4}{n} \ge (x_1x_2\cdots x_n)^4,
\end{align*}
i.e., 
\begin{align*}
512000 \ge n(x_1x_2\cdots x_n)^4,
\end{align*}
so 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1000^4}{n^4} \ge \frac{512000}{x_1^4 + x_2^4 + \dots + x_n^4}.
\end{align*}

Combining the two inequalities, we have 
\begin{align*}
512000 \ge n^3(x_1x_2\cdots x_n)^4,
\end{align*}
or 
\begin{align*}
80 \ge n(x_1x_2\cdots x_n)^4.
\end{align*}

However, the first inequality implies 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1000^4}{(x_1x_2\cdots x_n)^4} \ge n^3, 
\end{align*}
which is equivalent to 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1000^4}{80} &\ge n^3, 
\end{align*}
i.e., 
\begin{align*}
400\,000,000 &\ge n^3,
\end{align*}
which means 
\begin{align*}
\sqrt[3]{400\,000,000} &\ge n \ge 174.1.
\end{align*}

Therefore, the smallest possible $n$ here is always 175, since $174.1$ is not an integer. Thus, $n = 175$. <answer> 175 </answer>

